Related: https://github.com/vuejs/vetur/issues/534

Vetur extension defines two languages: `vue` and `vue-html`.

I can only use `languages.setLanguageConfiguration` to set indentation rule of the outer language `vue` but not the embedded `vue-html`.

With this API call, here's what I see:

```ts
export function registerLanguageConfigurations() {
  // languages.setLanguageConfiguration('vue', {
  //   indentationRules: {
  // 		increaseIndentPattern: /<(?!\?|(?:area|base|br|col|frame|hr|html|img|input|link|meta|param)\b|[^>]*\/>)([-_\.A-Za-z0-9]+)(?=\s|>)\b[^>]*>(?!.*<\/\1>)|<!--(?!.*-->)|\{[^}"']*$/,
  // 		decreaseIndentPattern: /^\s*(<\/(?!html)[-_\.A-Za-z0-9]+\b[^>]*>|-->|\})/
  //   },
  // });
  languages.setLanguageConfiguration('vue-html', {
    indentationRules: {
      increaseIndentPattern: /<(?!\?|(?:area|base|br|col|frame|hr|html|img|input|link|meta|param)\b|[^>]*\/>)([-_\.A-Za-z0-9]+)(?=\s|>)\b[^>]*>(?!.*<\/\1>)|<!--(?!.*-->)|\{[^}"']*$/,
      decreaseIndentPattern: /^\s*(<\/(?!html)[-_\.A-Za-z0-9]+\b[^>]*>|-->|\})/
    }
  });
}
```

![bug](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4033249/57496844-e899f280-7289-11e9-94d0-7145034d56ca.gif)

If I remove the commented-out call to set `indentationRules` of `vue` language, then it seems to work. However, I'm worried it'll affect other non `vue-html` regions such as css/javascript.

You can repro by:

- Checking out this branch of Vetur: https://github.com/vuejs/vetur/tree/embedded-indentation-rules
- Compile with

  ```bash
  yarn
  cd server && yarn && cd ..
  yarn compile
  ```
- Run the `client` debug config to test it

In short:
- In `vue-html` embedded in `vue`, I would expect setting `vue-html`'s indentation rules would affect move line up/down
- I have to set both indentation rules for `vue` and `vue-html` to achieve this, which would have some side effect

- VSCode Version: 1.33.1
- OS Version: Ubuntu 18.04.1 LTS

Steps to Reproduce:

Press Enter after typing an `if` or `for` statement in a C program without using curly braces.

Does this issue occur when all extensions are disabled?: Yes

Expected behaviour:
```
if(true)
    i++;

for(i=0; i<n; i++)
    j++;
```

Current behaviour:
```
if(true)
i++;

for(i=0; i<n; i++)
j++;
```

It's common in C/C++ programming to avoid using the curly braces after conditionals like `if` and `for` when the statement succeeding them is only one line. VSCode doesn't detect this and doesn't add an indentation automatically when enter is pressed. The indentation works fine with curly braces though. Would love this to be fixed since it disturbs the workflow and most other popular IDEs have this little feature already.

- open a WSL remote, install the C++ extension
- create a file 'main.c'
```
int main()
{
    return x;
}
```
- invoke Terminal > Run Acrive File
- error `Only files on disk can be run in the terminal`
